# Technical debt monitoring agent — preliminary rules

Read together with **software-quality/tech-debt-agent-design.md** (design decisions) and **software-quality/tech-debt-agent-research.md** (background research). This rule sketches how an agent should behave when we implement it; no code yet.

## Role

The agent monitors the codebase for signs of accumulating technical debt and, over time, will suggest concrete changes to reduce it. It should be informed by software engineering research on [technical debt measurement](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=technical+debt+measurement+software), [software quality metrics](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=software+quality+metrics+maintainability), and [code smell detection](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=code+smell+detection+refactoring).

## Scope and boundaries

- **Monitor first, suggest later.** Initially the agent focuses on measuring and reporting; suggestions are a later phase.
- **Evidence-based.** Prefer metrics and classifications that have empirical support (see research note for pointers).
- **Project-appropriate.** This is a Python/JS repo with scripts, data pipelines, and a small frontend. Metrics and thresholds should fit that context (e.g. script length, duplication, test coverage if present).

## Measurements to consider (see design doc for choices)

- Structural: file/function length, [cyclomatic complexity](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=cyclomatic+complexity+maintainability), duplication (clones).
- Debt indicators: [technical debt principal and interest](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=technical+debt+principal+interest), TODO/FIXME density, dependency freshness.
- Consistency: naming, style drift, dead or unused code.

Do not invent new metrics without grounding in the design doc or research note.

## Output and interaction

- Reports and findings live under **software-quality/** (or a designated output path defined in the design doc). Do not scatter ad-hoc quality comments elsewhere.
- When suggesting changes, cite which measurement or finding motivates the suggestion.
- Prefer small, reviewable improvements over large refactors.

